Examine the probabilities in the model: pick and compare some of the probability values. Do they make sense?

Answer: Yes

Explain.

Answer:

In the Naive Bayes model, using a training data set (train) of 5000 records, we want to predict the default payment next month based on contributions from various historic independent demographics information. so we set the default payment for next month as the dependent variable. Then we set the various demographics such as SEX, EDUCATION, and MARRIAGE as the independent variables we want our prediction to be based on. From the result above;

  1. For the probability of Default in Payment next month based on SEX demographics:

    • Female clients have a higher probability of not defaulting on payment next month than Male clients

    • Female clients also have a higher probability of defaulting on a payment next month than Male clients

  2. For the probability of Default in Payment next month based on Marriage demographics:

  • Single Clients have a higher probability of not defaulting on payment next month than married clients and other clients

  • Single Clients also have a higher probability of defaulting on payment next month than married clients and other clients

Final Thoughts: Using all this information/properties from independent variables, the model is predicting that the probability of a client not defaulting on payment is higher than a client defaulting on payment.

Repeat related steps in B.2. to perform testing and evaluation. Discuss the impact of Laplace smoothing.

Answer:

  1. For the probability of default in a payment next month based on repayment status in September(PAY_0):

    • clients who pay duly(-1) have the highest probability of not defaulting on payment next month but this has reduced in comparison to other clients that delay in repayment.

    • Also clients who pay duly(-1) have the highest probability of defaulting on payment next month but this has also reduced in comparison to other clients that delay in repayment.

  2. For the probability of default in a payment next month based on repayment status in September(PAY_2):

    • clients who pay duly(-1) have the highest probability of not defaulting on payment next month but this has reduced in comparison to other clients that delay in repayment.

    • Also clients who pay duly(-1) have the highest probability of defaulting on payment next month but this has also reduced in comparison to other clients that delay in repayment.

Final Thoughts: Laplace smoothing ensures the nonzero value of probabilities. So in our former model(without Laplace), we had zero values for the probability of not defaulting in 6 - 8 months in repayments status. After applying Laplace to our model, small nonzero probabilities were applied to these rare events to avoid overfitting.

The model still predicts the same probability of a client not defaulting on payment next month.

C. Classification with Decision Tree C.1. Basic Decision Tree Build a decision tree using up to three payment status variables as predictors. For example:

library("rpart")
library("rpart.plot")
dtPay <- rpart(default.payment.next.month ~ PAY_0 + PAY_2 + PAY_3,
            method="class",
            data=train, parms=list(split='information'), 
            minsplit=20, cp=0.02)

Also, visualize the decision tree using:

rpart.plot(dtPay, type=4, extra=1)

Examine the decision tree visualization, explain what it means, and whether it is reasonable.

Answer:

From our training data set of 5000 records, the decision tree was built based on three repayment status variables which are PAY_0, PAY_2, and PAY_3.

  • on the left side of the node, out of the total clients who pay duly and delay 1 month in repayment (4,493), the number of No for default in payment (3760) is higher than the number of yes for defaults in payment (733), so the decision for that node for default in payment is NO.

-on the right side of the node, out of the total clients who delay 2-8 months in repayment (507), the number of No for default in payment (146) is lower than the number of yes for default in payment (361), so the decision for that node for default in payment is YES

  • On the root node, out of the total clients for all the repayment status variables (5000), the number of No for default in payment (3760 + 146 = 3906) is higher than the number of yes for default in payment (733 + 361 = 1094), so the final decision for the root node for default in payment is NO.

Final Thought: Yes the decision tree is reasonable.

Again run the model on your test data and predict the outcome:

predict(nbPay, test[1,])
[1] No
Levels: No Yes

Answer:

The complexity parameter is used to control the size of the decision tree and select the optimal tree size. From my observation the higher the cp, the smaller and less complex the decision tree is. The smaller the cp, the more the decision tree is broken down into more nodes.
